observations.recommendation:
We recommended and
Management agreed that the
following actions be
undertaken for the
immediate disposal of
unserviceable property
items:
a. The Municipal GSO prepare an Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) covering all unserviceable property of the municipality as of date of preparation of the IIRUP and submit the same to the Municipal Disposal Committee;
b. The Disposal Committee conduct ocular inspection and recommend the mode of disposal to be undertaken;
c. The Disposal Committee decide and recommend, as a collegial body, one appraisal valuation for the property for disposal;
d. The Municipal Mayor acts on the recommendations of the Disposal Committee and cause the actual disposal of the unserviceable property items;
e. The Property Officer accomplish all pertinent portions of the IIRUP after the disposal of unserviceable property items and submit the accomplished form to the Municipal GSO who shall then report the same to the Disposal Committee;
f. The Disposal Committee issue a certification on the disposal addressed to the Municipal Accountant; and
g. The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary journal entries to drop the property items from the books of accounts and take up the proceeds from the sale of property, if any.

We recommended and
Management agreed that the:
a. Property and Accounting Units update their respective records and, thereafter, compare both records and note the discrepancies;
b. Property Unit prepare and submit to the Inventory Committee, with the latest RPCPPE, a list of PPE items which are recorded in the PPE Ledger Cards (PPELCs) but not included in the RPCPPE as well as PPE items which are included in the RPCPPE but not recorded in the PPELCs;
c. Inventory Committee prepare and submit a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) to this Office at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities; and
d. Property and Accounting Units reconcile the inventory count per RPCPPE with the property and accounting records within ten (10) days from rendition of the RPCPPE by the Inventory Committee, investigate/verify any differences, and prepare the appropriate adjustments on both records for reconciling items noted, and make accountable persons liable for shortages or losses of PPE items, if any.

We recommended that
Management:
a. Demand the immediate liquidation of cash advances which purpose/s have been served/completed;
b. Strictly enforce the full liquidation of cash advance before the grant of a new one and discontinue the practice of using unused cash advance for succeeding cash advance;
c. Consider designating disbursing officers, who should be properly bonded for such purpose, if necessary; and
d. Enforce the submission of the Municipal Accountant’s Certification that previous cash advances have been liquidated and accounted for in the books as a documentary requirement before a new cash advance is granted.

We recommended and Management agreed that:
a. Management determine the specific estimated useful life for each semi-expendable property, based on their experience on the life of their asset and considering the life spans contained in COA Circular No. 2022-004, and issue the corresponding policy/memorandum thereto and copy furnished the COA Auditor;
b. The Supply Officer prepare and issue updated ICS for semi-expendable property procured and issued to end-users in prior years;
c. The Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain Semi-Expendable Property Ledger Card; and
d. The Supply Officer prepare and maintain Semi-Expendable Property Card, Registry of Semi-Expendable Property Issued and Report of Semi-Expendable Property Issued.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:

Direct the Property and Accounting Units to update their respective records and, thereafter, compare and reconcile both records;

Ensure that the created Inventory Committee shall be temporarily relieved of all their regular duties until the conduct of the physical inventory taking is completed in three months or less;

Require the Inventory Committee to prepare and submit a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) to this Office at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities; and

Ensure that the Property and Accounting Units reconcile the inventory count per RPCPPE with the property and accounting records within ten (10) days from rendition of the RPCPPE by the Inventory Committee.

